Thanks for the food for thought.  I totally agree that our country did not have the moral quality needed to assess the situation nor did our leaders at the time have an honest, accurate assessment of what we were getting into.  We did not meet many of the tests required for getting involved.<br><br>
LBJ campaigned at the time on a peace platform, while supposedly planning to escalate the war.  Perhaps, it would have been wiser if we did not get involved...but the same was true of Korea, Bosnia, Somalia, etc.  <br><br>
There was one cartoon I liked that reflects a stable peace. It went something like this:  Two leaders from two third world countries wondered how to get out of their economic chaos.  One had an idea...declare war on the US!!!...and...lose!!!  It worked for Japan and Germany.  Our allies have had a rougher time.<br><br>
It appears that no war could truly meet your test.  Look at what was given away after the war.  There were many good and honorable people who protested our countries involvement in that war. Was our entrance to the war a contrived occurence...In other words were warnings about the potential raid on Pearl Harbor ignored by our leadership, knowing that the mass destruction heaped upon our soldiers is what it would take to rally the masses to accept war.<br><br>
Could we meet those tests...I not sure anyone's knowledge is that great.  There always seems to be hidden agenda's.  Thanks for your input.<br><br>
Perhaps, the war cost more...but I am thinking that so many lives have been lost in the Indonesian region according to Amnesty international that we could have made a difference with regards to Pol Pot...and others in the region like him.<br><br>
